<P>My third character was Bayes, in the Rehear&s;a which was judged a &s;ervice of danger, Mr. Frod|&s;ham, being e&s;teemed capital in the part; but the<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter"> opinion was wrong, for I had been &s;o familiarize to that kind of playing, and was &s;o much bett<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter"> &s;tage acquainted, that I obtained a complete vi<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter">|tory in &s;pight of partiality, which in general ob&s;tinate; yet mu&s;t be allowed often prai&s;e-wo<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter">|thy. Indeed Mr. Frod&s;ham was totally un<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter"> for that character, and his friends as well as th re&s;t of the audience would have found that ou had not five out of &s;ix &s;ub&s;cribed to whatever <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 letter">
